    category: "sacraments",
    tags: ["marriage", "dissolution", "Pauline privilege", "canon law", "1 Corinthians 7"],
    oneLiner: "The dissolution of a natural (non-sacramental) marriage between two unbaptized persons when one party is subsequently baptized and the other refuses to live in peace, based on 1 Corinthians 7:12-15.",
    body: "The Pauline Privilege, grounded in St. Paul's teaching in 1 Corinthians 7:12-15, permits the dissolution of a valid natural marriage between two unbaptized persons when one party later receives Baptism. Three conditions must be met: both spouses were unbaptized at the time of the marriage, one spouse subsequently receives Christian Baptism, and the unbaptized spouse departs or refuses to cohabit peacefully without offense to the Creator. The privilege is exercised at the moment the baptized party enters a new marriage. This is not an annulment (which declares that no valid marriage existed) but an actual dissolution of a valid bond, possible because the original marriage, while valid, was not sacramental. The Church teaches that only sacramental marriage between two baptized persons is absolutely indissoluble.",
    example: "A man and woman, both unbaptized, marry in a civil ceremony. Years later, the wife converts to Catholicism and is baptized. Her husband, hostile to her faith, refuses to live peacefully and leaves. The wife may invoke the Pauline Privilege to dissolve the first marriage and marry a Catholic man in the Church.",
    whyItMatters: "The Pauline Privilege demonstrates the Church's careful distinction between natural and sacramental marriage, showing that while all valid marriages are sacred, the sacramental bond between the baptized possesses a unique and absolute indissolubility.",
