    category: "sacraments",
    tags: ["marriage", "papal dissolution", "Petrine privilege", "non-sacramental"],
    oneLiner: "The Pope's authority to dissolve a valid non-sacramental marriage in favor of the faith, extending beyond the Pauline Privilege to cases where at least one party was baptized at the time of the original marriage.",
    body: "The Petrine Privilege (also called the Privilege of the Faith or the Favor of the Faith) is an extension of papal authority beyond the Pauline Privilege. While the Pauline Privilege applies only when both parties were unbaptized, the Petrine Privilege can dissolve a valid marriage where at least one party was unbaptized at the time of the wedding—meaning the marriage was not sacramental. The Pope exercises this power directly, through the Dicastery for the Doctrine of the Faith, on a case-by-case basis. Cases are rigorously investigated to ensure that the original marriage was indeed non-sacramental and that there is a genuine pastoral reason (favor of the faith) for the dissolution. This privilege has been invoked more frequently since the mid-twentieth century as cross-cultural and interfaith marriages have become more common.",
