    category: "sacraments",
    tags: ["marriage", "canon law", "convalidation", "radical sanation"],
    oneLiner: "A retroactive healing of an invalid marriage 'at the root' by Church authority, making it valid from its beginning without requiring the couple to renew consent.",
    body: "Sanatio in radice (Latin for 'healing at the root') is an extraordinary canonical act by which the Church retroactively validates an invalid marriage from the moment of its original celebration, without requiring the renewal of consent. It is granted by the diocesan bishop or the Holy See and is used when there is a canonical impediment or defect of form that made the original wedding invalid, but both parties gave genuine matrimonial consent that still persists. The sanation removes the impediment, dispenses from the requirement to renew consent, and causes the marriage to be considered valid from its inception. This is particularly useful when one party is unaware of the invalidity and asking them to renew consent would cause confusion or marital discord, or when a party is incapacitated or deceased.",
