    term: "Eucharistic Fast History and Development",
    category: "sacraments",
    tags: ["Eucharist", "fasting", "Communion", "discipline", "history"],
    oneLiner: "The historical development of the eucharistic fast from the ancient practice of fasting from midnight to the current one-hour fast before receiving Holy Communion.",
    body: "The Eucharistic fast—abstaining from food and drink before receiving Communion—dates to the earliest centuries of the Church, rooted in the belief that the greatest of all foods should be received with reverence and bodily preparation. For most of Church history, the fast required complete abstinence from food and drink (including water) from midnight until Communion. Pope Pius XII, recognizing that this discipline prevented many from receiving Communion (especially at afternoon and evening Masses), reduced the fast to three hours for food and one hour for liquids in 1957. Pope Paul VI further reduced it to the current one-hour fast before Communion in 1964. Water and medicine have never broken the fast under the current discipline. The elderly, the sick, and their caregivers are exempt from the fast altogether.",
    example: "Before 1957, a Catholic attending a noon Mass would have eaten nothing since midnight—twelve hours of fasting. Today, a Catholic attending the same Mass need only fast from 11:00 AM, making Communion accessible to those with medical conditions or demanding schedules.",
    whyItMatters: "The history of the Eucharistic fast illustrates how the Church adapts its disciplines to pastoral needs while preserving the underlying principle: approaching the Lord's Body and Blood requires both spiritual and bodily preparation.",
