    category: "sacraments",
    tags: ["Eucharist", "chalice", "both species", "liturgical practice"],
    oneLiner: "The history and theology of receiving Holy Communion under both the forms of bread and wine, restored as an option for the laity after Vatican II.",
    body: "In the early Church, Communion under both kinds (bread and wine) was the universal practice. From the twelfth century onward, the chalice was gradually restricted to the clergy in the Latin Rite for practical reasons (risk of spilling the Precious Blood, scrupulosity, and large congregations) and theological ones (the Council of Trent defined that the whole Christ is present under either species alone). The Second Vatican Council's Sacrosanctum Concilium permitted the restoration of Communion under both kinds for the laity in certain cases, and subsequent legislation expanded these permissions. The General Instruction of the Roman Missal now allows bishops' conferences to determine when and how the chalice is offered. The practice affirms the fuller sign value of the Eucharistic banquet while the Church continues to teach that reception under one kind alone gives the communicant the full grace of the sacrament.",
