    oneLiner: "The reception of Holy Communion by the dying as 'food for the journey' from this life to eternal life, considered the most important sacrament for the departing Christian.",
    body: "Viaticum (Latin for 'provision for the journey') is Holy Communion given to a person in danger of death. The Church considers it the most important of the last sacraments—more essential even than Anointing of the Sick—because it is Christ himself accompanying the dying person on the journey from earthly life to the Father's house. Canon law obliges pastors to ensure that the dying receive Viaticum and permits its reception even if the person has already received Communion that day. The rite includes a special renewal of baptismal promises and the formula 'May the Lord Jesus Christ protect you and lead you to eternal life,' distinct from the ordinary Communion formula. Viaticum may be administered under both kinds, and in urgent circumstances, any Catholic may bring the Eucharist to a dying person.",
    example: "A hospital chaplain is called at 2:00 AM to the bedside of a dying patient. The chaplain leads the family in prayer, helps the patient renew baptismal promises, and administers Viaticum, placing a small portion of the consecrated host on the patient's tongue as the family prays together.",
