    oneLiner: "The historical name and understanding of the sacrament now called Anointing of the Sick, formerly administered only to those at the point of death.",
    body: "Extreme Unction ('last anointing') was the common name for the sacrament of the sick from the medieval period until the Second Vatican Council. In practice, it was typically delayed until the person was at or very near death, often received while unconscious. The Council of Trent (1551) defined that the sacrament was instituted by Christ and promulgated by the Apostle James (James 5:14-15), conferring grace, remission of sins, and comfort to the sick. However, Trent also noted it was especially appropriate for those 'at the point of departing this life.' Vatican II's Sacrosanctum Concilium renamed it 'Anointing of the Sick' and broadened its administration to anyone seriously ill, elderly, or facing surgery, not only the imminently dying. This shift recovered the sacrament's original purpose as healing prayer for the sick rather than solely preparation for death.",
    example: "Before Vatican II, families often waited to call the priest until the dying person had lost consciousness, fearing that calling for 'Last Rites' would frighten the patient. After the Council, Catholics were encouraged to request the sacrament earlier during illness, when the sick person could participate consciously.",
    whyItMatters: "The evolution from Extreme Unction to Anointing of the Sick illustrates how the Church recovers the fuller meaning of its sacraments through liturgical renewal, making the healing grace of Christ more accessible to the faithful.",
