    oneLiner: "The historical rite of cutting hair to signify entry into the clerical state, abolished by Pope Paul VI in 1972 as part of the reform of minor orders.",
    body: "Tonsure was the liturgical rite by which a man was admitted into the clerical state, receiving from the bishop a ceremonial cutting of hair in the form of a crown (the corona) symbolizing the crown of thorns and dedication to God's service. Dating from at least the fifth century, tonsure was not itself an order but the gateway to the clerical state, after which a man could receive minor orders, major orders, and eventually priestly ordination. The tonsured cleric was bound by certain obligations including the daily recitation of the Divine Office and the wearing of clerical dress. In 1972, Pope Paul VI's motu proprio Ministeria Quaedam abolished tonsure along with the minor orders of porter, exorcist, and subdeacon, replacing them with the installed ministries of lector and acolyte. Today, entry into the clerical state occurs at diaconal ordination.",
    example: "In the old rite, a young seminarian knelt before the bishop who cut five locks of hair in the form of a cross while the candidate recited Psalm 16: 'The Lord is the portion of my inheritance and my cup; it is you who will restore my inheritance to me.' He rose as a cleric, set apart for sacred service.",
    whyItMatters: "The history of tonsure illustrates how the Church's external disciplines evolve over time while the underlying reality—total consecration to God's service—remains constant across every era of Church life.",
