    oneLiner: "The four lower clerical orders—porter, lector, exorcist, and acolyte—that historically preceded the major orders of subdeacon, deacon, and priest, reformed by Paul VI in 1972.",
    body: "The minor orders developed in the early centuries as the Church organized liturgical and pastoral functions into a structured hierarchy. The four minor orders were: Porter (ostiarius), who guarded the church doors and rang the bells; Lector, who read the Scriptures at liturgy; Exorcist, who prayed prayers of deliverance over catechumens; and Acolyte, who assisted the priest at the altar and carried candles. These orders were conferred by the bishop with specific rites and instruments (e.g., the lector received the lectionary, the acolyte received a candlestick). By the medieval period, the minor orders had largely become ceremonial stepping-stones to priesthood rather than functional ministries. Paul VI's 1972 reform suppressed the orders of porter and exorcist entirely and transformed lector and acolyte from clerical orders into 'installed ministries' open to laymen (and since 2021 by Pope Francis's Spiritus Domini, open to women as well).",
    example: "In the pre-1972 seminary system, a man would receive tonsure in his first year, then porter and lector, then exorcist and acolyte in subsequent years, ascending step by step through the clerical ranks before receiving subdiaconate, diaconate, and priesthood.",
