    tags: ["deacon", "permanent diaconate", "Vatican II", "ordained ministry", "service"],
    oneLiner: "The restored permanent diaconate, reestablished by Vatican II, in which ordained men—often married—serve the Church through ministries of Word, liturgy, and charity.",
    body: "The permanent diaconate, one of the oldest ordained ministries, had effectively disappeared in the Latin Rite by the medieval period, surviving only as a transitional step to priesthood. The Second Vatican Council's Lumen Gentium (1964) restored it as a permanent vocation, and Pope Paul VI implemented this in 1967 with the motu proprio Sacrum Diaconatus Ordinem. Permanent deacons receive the Sacrament of Holy Orders through the imposition of hands and prayer of consecration by a bishop. They may baptize, witness marriages, proclaim the Gospel, preach, preside at funerals, and administer certain sacramentals. Married men may be ordained deacons, but once ordained, a deacon whose wife dies may not remarry without special dispensation. Today there are over 48,000 permanent deacons worldwide, with the majority in the United States, serving in parishes, hospitals, prisons, and social ministries.",
