    oneLiner: "The earliest Christian writings outside the New Testament, composed by authors who knew the Apostles or their immediate disciples, providing a vital bridge between Scripture and later tradition.",
    body: "The Apostolic Fathers are a collection of first- and second-century Christian writings that offer an invaluable window into the life, worship, and theology of the earliest Church. The corpus typically includes 1 Clement (a letter from the bishop of Rome to Corinth, c. 96 AD), the seven letters of Ignatius of Antioch (c. 107 AD, who coined the term 'Catholic Church'), the letter and martyrdom of Polycarp, the Didache (a manual of Christian practice), the Epistle of Barnabas, the Shepherd of Hermas, and the Epistle to Diognetus. These texts witness to the real presence in the Eucharist, episcopal authority, baptismal practice, and the expectation of martyrdom as normative features of Christian life from the very beginning.",
    example: "Ignatius of Antioch, writing to the Smyrnaeans around 107 AD while being transported to Rome for martyrdom, states that the Eucharist 'is the flesh of our Savior Jesus Christ'—one of the earliest explicit witnesses to the doctrine of the Real Presence.",
    whyItMatters: "The Apostolic Fathers demonstrate that Catholic doctrines such as the Real Presence, apostolic succession, and episcopal governance are not later inventions but were held from the earliest post-apostolic generation.",
