    oneLiner: "A vast anthology of Eastern Christian spiritual texts on prayer of the heart and inner stillness, compiled in the eighteenth century but drawing on writings from the fourth to fifteenth centuries.",
    body: "The Philokalia (Greek for 'love of the beautiful') is a collection of texts on contemplative prayer written by masters of the Eastern Christian tradition between the fourth and fifteenth centuries, compiled by Sts. Nikodemos the Hagiorite and Makarios of Corinth in 1782. The collection includes works by Evagrius Ponticus, Maximus the Confessor, John Climacus, Symeon the New Theologian, Gregory Palamas, and many others. Its central theme is hesychasm—the practice of inner stillness and the prayer of the heart (often the Jesus Prayer: 'Lord Jesus Christ, Son of God, have mercy on me, a sinner'). Through purification, illumination, and theosis (divinization), the practitioner is drawn into the uncreated light of God. While rooted in the Orthodox tradition, the Philokalia has become increasingly valued by Catholic readers, especially after Vatican II encouraged engagement with Eastern Christian spirituality.",
