    term: "Rule of St. Augustine",
    category: "tradition",
    tags: ["Augustine", "rule", "community life", "Augustinian", "canons regular"],
    oneLiner: "The oldest monastic rule in the Western Church, attributed to St. Augustine of Hippo, emphasizing communal living, shared goods, and unity of heart and mind directed toward God.",
    body: "The Rule of St. Augustine, dating to the early fifth century, is the shortest and oldest of the major Western religious rules. Based on Augustine's Letter 211 and a companion document called the Praeceptum, it takes the community of believers in Acts 4:32 ('one heart and one soul') as its ideal. Unlike the detailed prescriptions of Benedict's Rule, Augustine's Rule focuses on interior dispositions: charity, humility, mutual correction, and the renunciation of private ownership. All things are held in common, distributed according to need. The Rule emphasizes that external observances are worthless without interior love. It has been adopted by a remarkable diversity of communities including the Augustinian Friars, the Dominicans, the Premonstratensians, the Servites, and many congregations of women religious, each adding their own constitutions to its broad framework.",
