    category: "tradition",
    tags: ["Francis of Assisi", "Franciscan", "poverty", "rule", "mendicant"],
    oneLiner: "The Regula Bullata approved by Pope Honorius III in 1223, establishing radical poverty, itinerant preaching, and minority as the foundations of Franciscan life.",
    body: "The Rule of St. Francis exists in several versions. The Earlier Rule (Regula non Bullata, 1221) was a lengthy, Scripture-saturated document reflecting the spontaneity of the early fraternity. The Later Rule (Regula Bullata, 1223), approved by Pope Honorius III, is the definitive text: twelve concise chapters establishing the Franciscan way of life. Its hallmarks are radical poverty (friars may own nothing individually or communally), itinerant preaching, manual labor as the ordinary means of support with begging permitted when work is unavailable, and 'minority'—living as the least in society. The Rule requires obedience to the Pope and to local superiors, prescribes the Divine Office, and establishes procedures for accepting new members. Francis insisted that his Rule was simply the Gospel lived literally, and its radical simplicity distinguished the Franciscan movement from the established monastic orders of its day.",
    example: "Francis wrote that the friars should 'not make anything their own, neither house, nor place, nor anything at all' but should go through the world 'as pilgrims and strangers,' depending entirely on God's providence. This radical itinerancy contrasted sharply with the stability of Benedictine monasticism.",
