    term: "Carmelite Rule",
    category: "tradition",
    tags: ["Carmelite", "contemplation", "Elijah", "Mount Carmel", "rule"],
    oneLiner: "The Rule given to the Carmelite hermits of Mount Carmel by St. Albert of Jerusalem around 1207, emphasizing solitude, silence, continuous prayer, and contemplative devotion.",
    body: "The Carmelite Rule (Formula of Life) was composed by St. Albert, Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem, around 1206-1214 for a group of hermits living on Mount Carmel in the Holy Land. It is remarkably brief—only sixteen short chapters—and prescribes a life of silence, solitude, and unceasing prayer. Each hermit is assigned a separate cell where he is to 'meditate day and night on the law of the Lord and keep watch in prayer.' The community gathers daily for the Eucharist and observes strict fasting and abstinence. When the Carmelites migrated to Europe in the thirteenth century, the Rule was modified (1247) to allow communal living and apostolic ministry, but its contemplative core remained. The Teresian reform of the sixteenth century, led by St. Teresa of Avila and St. John of the Cross, returned to the primitive Rule's emphasis on solitude and interior prayer, producing some of the greatest mystical literature in Christian history.",
