    oneLiner: "The governing documents of the Order of Preachers, establishing the unique Dominican synthesis of contemplative prayer, rigorous study, community life, and itinerant preaching.",
    body: "The Dominican Constitutions, first compiled under St. Dominic de Guzman and formally adopted at the Order's General Chapters of 1220 and 1228, created a revolutionary form of religious life. Building on the Rule of St. Augustine, Dominic added three distinctive elements: first, rigorous intellectual formation, making study not merely useful but a religious obligation; second, democratic governance through elected superiors and representative chapters at every level; and third, dispensation from observances (even choir duties) when preaching or study required it, establishing the principle that contemplation should overflow into preaching ('contemplata aliis tradere'—to hand on to others the fruits of contemplation). The Constitutions also established the novel practice of corporate poverty (the Order itself, not just individual friars, was to be mendicant) and created a highly mobile fraternity of scholar-preachers who could be sent wherever the need was greatest.",
