    body: "The Constitutions of the Society of Jesus, composed by St. Ignatius of Loyola between 1541 and 1556, represent a radical departure from traditional religious rules. Ignatius eliminated the choral recitation of the Divine Office, fixed penances, and distinctive religious habit—all hallmarks of older orders—to create maximum flexibility for mission. The Constitutions emphasize discernment (finding God in all things), obedience to the Pope and to superiors (described as obedience of understanding and will, not mere external compliance), an exceptionally long formation process (up to fifteen years), and the integration of contemplation with apostolic action. The document is organized around the journey of a Jesuit: admission, formation, incorporation into the body, mission, and governance. A unique feature is the Fourth Vow of special obedience to the Pope regarding missions, making Jesuits available for deployment wherever the Pope sees the greatest need.",
    example: "When Francis Xavier received a letter from Ignatius reassigning him from teaching in Rome to missionary work in India and Japan, he departed within days, exemplifying the Jesuit ideal of total availability. The Constitutions made such radical mobility possible by eliminating attachment to place, routine, and fixed observances.",
