    body: "The Congregation of the Oratory, founded by St. Philip Neri in Rome in 1575, represents a unique form of priestly life. Oratorians are secular (diocesan) priests who live in community but take no religious vows. Each Oratory is autonomous, bound to its local community in perpetuity. Members are united not by vows but by mutual charity and a shared commitment to prayer, preaching, and the care of souls. The Oratorian day centers on communal prayer, the celebration of Mass, and the distinctive practice of 'Oratory exercises'—informal gatherings for prayer, Scripture reading, sacred music, and spiritual conversation that Philip Neri pioneered as a form of evangelization. The Oratorian tradition has produced notable figures including Cardinal Newman, who founded the Birmingham Oratory, and Father Frederick Faber, founder of the London Oratory. Oratorians have been known for their cultivation of sacred music, beautiful liturgy, and intellectual life.",
