    id: "mex-trappist-life",
    term: "Trappist Life",
    category: "tradition",
    tags: ["Trappist", "Cistercian", "silence", "monasticism", "contemplation"],
    oneLiner: "The austere contemplative life of the Order of Cistercians of the Strict Observance (Trappists), characterized by silence, manual labor, and a rhythm of prayer centered on the Divine Office.",
    body: "The Trappists (formally the Order of Cistercians of the Strict Observance, O.C.S.O.) emerged from the seventeenth-century reform of the Cistercian monastery of La Trappe in Normandy under Abbot Armand-Jean de Rance. Trappist life follows the Rule of St. Benedict in its most rigorous interpretation: monks rise at 3:00 AM for Vigils, chant the full Divine Office throughout the day, observe extensive periods of silence, abstain perpetually from meat, and engage in manual labor (often farming, brewing, or cheese-making). The atmosphere of silence is not mere absence of speech but a positive cultivation of listening—to God, to Scripture, and to the movements of the heart. Famous Trappist monasteries include Gethsemani (home of Thomas Merton), Sept-Fons in France, and Mount Melleray in Ireland. Trappist spirituality has influenced many laypeople through Merton's writings and the growing movement of Trappist oblates.",
    example: "Thomas Merton described entering the Abbey of Gethsemani and finding in its silence not emptiness but fullness: 'The silence of the forest, the peace of the early morning wind moving the branches of the trees, the solitude in which the Creator speaks in the essence of things.' His Seven Storey Mountain introduced millions to Trappist life.",
    whyItMatters: "Trappist life witnesses to the modern world that silence, simplicity, and contemplation are not relics of the past but essential human needs, offering a counter-cultural testimony to the primacy of God in an age of noise and distraction.",
