    tags: ["Norbertine", "Premonstratensian", "canons regular", "Norbert", "liturgy"],
    oneLiner: "The Order of Canons Regular founded by St. Norbert in 1120, combining the contemplative life of Augustinian canons with active pastoral ministry, especially liturgical celebration and preaching.",
    body: "The Premonstratensian Order (also known as the Norbertines or White Canons from their white habits) was founded by St. Norbert of Xanten at Premontre, France, in 1120. Unlike monks who are primarily contemplative, Premonstratensians are canons regular—priests living in community under the Rule of St. Augustine, dedicated both to the solemn celebration of the liturgy and to active pastoral work in parishes, schools, and missions. Their charism combines the stability and prayer life of monastic observance with the flexibility to serve in parishes and other apostolates. The Order was instrumental in evangelizing northern Europe, particularly the Baltic region, and experienced a great renewal after being nearly destroyed during the Reformation and French Revolution. Today Premonstratensian abbeys serve parishes, run schools, and maintain a strong commitment to communal celebration of the Divine Office as the heart of their apostolic life.",
    example: "At Daylesford Abbey in Pennsylvania, Norbertine canons chant the full Divine Office together, celebrate solemn liturgies, and then head out to staff local parishes, teach in schools, and serve as hospital chaplains—embodying the Premonstratensian synthesis of contemplation and action.",
