    category: "tradition",
    tags: ["Mercedarian", "ransom", "captives", "Peter Nolasco", "mercy"],
    oneLiner: "The Order of the Blessed Virgin Mary of Mercy, founded in 1218 to ransom Christians captured and enslaved by Moors, uniquely vowing to offer themselves as hostages if necessary.",
    body: "The Order of the Blessed Virgin Mary of Mercy (Mercedarians) was founded in Barcelona in 1218 by St. Peter Nolasco, with the encouragement of St. Raymond of Penyafort and King James I of Aragon. Its founding purpose was extraordinary: to ransom Christians captured and enslaved during the conflicts between Christian and Muslim kingdoms in medieval Spain and North Africa. Mercedarians took a unique fourth vow (in addition to poverty, chastity, and obedience): to remain as hostages in place of captives whose faith was in danger, even at the cost of their own lives. Over the centuries, Mercedarian friars ransomed thousands of captives and many gave their lives in captivity. As the historical circumstances of their founding charism changed, the Order adapted its mission to serve all forms of captivity: poverty, addiction, imprisonment, and spiritual bondage. Today Mercedarians work in prisons, with refugees, and in marginalized communities across the world.",
    example: "In the thirteenth century, Mercedarian friars would travel to North African markets where Christian slaves were sold, negotiate their ransom, and personally escort them home. When funds ran short, friars sometimes remained behind in chains as surety—a literal fulfillment of 'greater love has no man than this.'",
    whyItMatters: "The Mercedarian charism reveals the radical lengths to which Christian charity can extend, transforming the works of mercy from pious sentiment into heroic, life-risking action on behalf of the captive and enslaved.",
