    id: "mex-brown-scapular-promises",
    term: "Brown Scapular Promises",
    category: "devotions",
    tags: ["scapular", "Carmelite", "Mary", "promises", "Simon Stock"],
    oneLiner: "The tradition that Our Lady promised St. Simon Stock that whoever dies wearing the Brown Scapular of Our Lady of Mount Carmel will not suffer eternal fire.",
    body: "The Brown Scapular devotion is rooted in a vision attributed to St. Simon Stock, Prior General of the Carmelites, in 1251, in which the Blessed Virgin Mary presented him with the scapular and declared: 'Whoever dies wearing this scapular shall not suffer eternal fire.' A second promise, known as the Sabbatine Privilege (associated with a Bull attributed to Pope John XXII in 1322), holds that Mary will intercede for scapular-wearers in Purgatory, especially on the Saturday after their death. The Church has affirmed the Brown Scapular as a sacramental (a sacred sign that prepares one to receive grace) while carefully noting that it is not a magical guarantee of salvation but a sign of consecration to Mary and a commitment to live according to the Carmelite spirit of prayer and devotion. The scapular must be invested by a priest or deacon, and the wearer should strive to live a life of prayer, frequent the sacraments, and practice devotion to Our Lady.",
    example: "Before the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, many Christian sailors wore the Brown Scapular into battle. After the unexpected victory, devotion to the scapular and to Our Lady of Mount Carmel spread rapidly throughout the Catholic world.",
    whyItMatters: "The Brown Scapular promises express the Church's confidence in Mary's maternal intercession while teaching that genuine devotion must be accompanied by a life of prayer, sacramental practice, and conversion of heart.",
