    oneLiner: "A sacramental associated with the conversion of non-believers and the healing of the sick, given in apparitions to Sister Justine Bisqueyburu of the Daughters of Charity in 1840.",
    body: "The Green Scapular originated in visions received by Sister Justine Bisqueyburu, a Daughter of Charity, between 1840 and 1846. Unlike the Brown Scapular, the Green Scapular does not require formal enrollment and may be given to anyone—including non-Catholics and the unbaptized—as a means of obtaining conversion, return to the sacraments, or physical healing. One side bears an image of Mary, the other a heart pierced by a sword, with the prayer: 'Immaculate Heart of Mary, pray for us now and at the hour of our death.' The person giving the scapular need only place it on or near the intended recipient and pray the associated prayer daily. Approved by Pope Pius IX in 1863, the Green Scapular has been associated with numerous accounts of conversion and healing, particularly of persons who had abandoned the faith or were resistant to spiritual approaches.",
