    id: "mex-miraculous-medal-story",
    term: "Miraculous Medal Story",
    category: "devotions",
    tags: ["Miraculous Medal", "Catherine Laboure", "apparition", "Immaculate Conception"],
    oneLiner: "The full story of how St. Catherine Laboure received the design for the Medal of the Immaculate Conception from the Blessed Virgin Mary in 1830, and the extraordinary graces that followed its distribution.",
    body: "In November 1830, the Blessed Virgin Mary appeared to St. Catherine Laboure, a novice of the Daughters of Charity in Paris, showing her a medal to be struck and distributed. The front depicted Mary standing on a globe, crushing a serpent, with rays of light streaming from her hands and the inscription 'O Mary, conceived without sin, pray for us who have recourse to thee.' The reverse showed the letter M surmounted by a cross, with the hearts of Jesus and Mary below. Catherine's confessor, Father Aladel, arranged for 1,500 medals to be struck in 1832. Almost immediately, reports of conversions, healings, and protections multiplied so dramatically that the medal became known as 'Miraculous.' The most famous conversion was that of Alphonse Ratisbonne, a hostile anti-Catholic who experienced a vision of Our Lady while wearing the medal and was baptized. Catherine's identity as the visionary remained secret until shortly before her death in 1876.",
    example: "In January 1842, Alphonse Ratisbonne, a French Jew who detested Catholicism, reluctantly agreed to wear the Miraculous Medal as a challenge. Days later, in the Church of Sant'Andrea delle Fratte in Rome, he experienced a vision of Our Lady exactly as depicted on the medal and immediately sought Baptism.",
    whyItMatters: "The Miraculous Medal story demonstrates the power of Marian devotion and sacramentals in the Church's evangelizing mission, and anticipated the dogmatic definition of the Immaculate Conception by twenty-four years.",
