    body: "The Medal of St. Benedict is one of the oldest and most honored medals in the Church, with origins tracing to the fifteenth century and formal papal approval from Benedict XIV in 1742. The front depicts St. Benedict holding a cross and his Rule, with the word 'PAX' and a raven with poisoned bread (recalling a murder attempt he survived). The reverse features a cross with the letters C.S.S.M.L.—N.D.S.M.D. ('May the Holy Cross be my light—May the dragon never be my guide') and around the margin V.R.S.N.S.M.V.—S.M.Q.L.I.V.B. ('Begone Satan! Never tempt me with your vanities—What you offer me is evil. Drink the poison yourself!'). The medal is widely used in the blessing of homes, placed in foundations of buildings, and worn as personal protection. It is also used by exorcists as a sacramental in the ministry of deliverance. A Jubilee version was struck in 1880 for the 1400th anniversary of Benedict's birth.",
