    body: "The First Friday Devotion originates in the apparitions of Jesus to St. Margaret Mary Alacoque at Paray-le-Monial, France, between 1673 and 1675. Jesus revealed His Sacred Heart burning with love for humanity and pierced by ingratitude, and requested reparatory Communion on the first Friday of each month. He made twelve promises to those who practice this devotion, including peace in families, consolation in trials, blessings on undertakings, and a refuge in life and death. The 'Great Promise' states that those who receive Communion on nine consecutive First Fridays will not die without receiving the last sacraments and that 'My Heart shall be their secure refuge in that last hour.' Theologians clarify that this promise presupposes genuine devotion and a sincere desire for conversion, not mechanical compliance. The devotion has been endorsed by numerous popes and remains one of the most practiced devotions in the Catholic world.",
    example: "A parish maintains a First Friday schedule each month: morning Mass with exposition of the Blessed Sacrament, the Litany of the Sacred Heart, and an hour of reparatory adoration. Many parishioners track their nine consecutive First Fridays on prayer cards kept in their missals.",
