    body: "The Franciscan Crown Rosary (Seraphic Rosary) consists of seven decades of Hail Marys, each meditating on a joy of Mary: the Annunciation, the Visitation, the Nativity of Jesus, the Adoration of the Magi, the Finding of Jesus in the Temple, the Resurrection appearances to Mary, and the Assumption and Coronation. Tradition holds that a young Franciscan novice in 1422 was accustomed to weaving a crown of flowers for a statue of Mary. When he entered religious life and could no longer gather flowers, the Blessed Virgin appeared and taught him this spiritual crown of prayers as a substitute. Two additional Hail Marys are added at the end to complete seventy-two, corresponding to a tradition about Mary's age at her Assumption. The devotion carries a plenary indulgence under the usual conditions and has been a distinctive feature of Franciscan Marian piety for six centuries, offering a joyful complement to the more sorrowful meditations of the traditional Rosary.",
    example: "In a Franciscan friary, the community gathers each morning to pray the Crown Rosary before Mass, meditating on Mary's joys rather than her sorrows. The practice sets a tone of gratitude and hope for the day ahead, reflecting the Franciscan spirit of joy.",
    whyItMatters: "The Franciscan Crown Rosary balances the Church's meditation on Mary's sorrows with an equally rich contemplation of her joys, embodying the Franciscan charism of finding joy in God's gifts even amid life's trials.",
