    body: "The Rosary of the Seven Joys (distinct from but related to the Franciscan Crown) focuses specifically on the joyful dimensions of Mary's life as a path of meditation for the faithful. While the precise form varies by tradition, common joys meditated upon include the Annunciation and Mary's fiat, the Visitation and the Magnificat, the birth of Jesus, the Epiphany, the Finding of Jesus in the Temple, the Resurrection, and Mary's Assumption and Coronation in heaven. Some forms add the joy of Pentecost. This devotion emphasizes that Mary's life, while marked by profound suffering, was fundamentally characterized by joy—the joy of bearing God in her womb, of witnessing His ministry, and of sharing in His triumph over death. The devotion serves as a corrective to any spirituality that dwells exclusively on suffering, reminding the faithful that the Christian life is ultimately ordered toward joy.",
