    term: "Chaplet of Divine Mercy Deeper",
    category: "devotions",
    tags: ["Divine Mercy", "Faustina", "chaplet", "three o'clock", "promises"],
    oneLiner: "A deeper exploration of the Chaplet of Divine Mercy given to St. Faustina Kowalska, its theological foundations, promises, and connection to the Hour of Great Mercy.",
    body: "The Chaplet of Divine Mercy was dictated by Jesus to St. Faustina Kowalska in Vilnius in 1935. Prayed on ordinary rosary beads, it consists of offering the Eternal Father 'the Body and Blood, Soul and Divinity of Your dearly beloved Son, Our Lord Jesus Christ, in atonement for our sins and those of the whole world,' followed on the small beads by 'For the sake of His sorrowful Passion, have mercy on us and on the whole world.' Its theological depth lies in its sacrificial character: the one praying is not merely asking for mercy but mystically offering Christ's own sacrifice to the Father. Jesus told Faustina that He desired the chaplet to be prayed especially at three o'clock (the Hour of Great Mercy, corresponding to His death on the Cross) and at the bedside of the dying, promising that 'even if there were a sinner most hardened, if he were to recite this chaplet only once, he would receive grace from My infinite mercy.' The devotion was universally promoted after John Paul II canonized Faustina in 2000.",
    example: "At 3:00 PM each day, a hospital chaplain pauses in the chapel to pray the Chaplet, then visits the rooms of the critically ill, praying the chaplet at the bedsides of the dying as Jesus requested, entrusting each soul to Divine Mercy at the hour when Christ died for the world.",
