    id: "mex-triduum-devotional",
    term: "Triduum Devotional Practice",
    category: "devotions",
    tags: ["triduum", "three days", "prayer", "preparation", "feast days"],
    oneLiner: "The devotional practice of three days of prayer before a feast day or for a special intention, a shorter and more intense form of the novena tradition.",
    body: "A devotional triduum (Latin for 'three days') is a period of three days of focused prayer, typically preceding a feast day or offered for a particular intention. Distinct from the Easter Triduum (the liturgical celebration of Holy Thursday through Easter Sunday), the devotional triduum is a popular prayer practice in many Catholic cultures. It typically involves three consecutive days of special Masses, exposition of the Blessed Sacrament, specific prayers, and preaching. Triduums may be celebrated before the feast of a parish patron saint, before First Communion or Confirmation classes receive the sacraments, or in times of community need. The three-day structure recalls biblical patterns of preparation: Jonah's three days in the whale, the three days between Christ's death and Resurrection, and the ancient Christian practice of three days of fasting before Baptism. Triduums offer a more accessible form of extended prayer than the nine-day novena while maintaining the principle that spiritual preparation requires dedicated time.",
    example: "A parish celebrates a triduum before the feast of its patron, St. Anthony: three evenings of exposition, rosary, a brief reflection on an aspect of the saint's life, and Benediction. The triduum builds anticipation for the feast and deepens the community's connection to its patron.",
    whyItMatters: "The triduum devotional practice teaches Catholics that important moments in the spiritual life deserve intentional preparation, and that even a short period of focused prayer can deepen receptivity to God's grace.",
