    id: "mex-forty-hours-devotion-history",
    term: "Forty Hours Devotion History",
    category: "devotions",
    tags: ["Forty Hours", "exposition", "adoration", "Eucharist", "history"],
    oneLiner: "The history of the Forty Hours Devotion, a practice of continuous Eucharistic exposition for forty hours commemorating the time Christ's body lay in the tomb, tracing from its sixteenth-century Italian origins to its worldwide spread.",
    body: "The Forty Hours Devotion (Quarant'Ore) originated in Milan in the 1530s, likely through the initiative of St. Anthony Mary Zaccaria and the Capuchin friars, during a time of plague and war. The devotion consists of approximately forty hours of continuous exposition of the Blessed Sacrament, recalling the forty hours between Christ's death on the Cross (3:00 PM Friday) and His Resurrection (early Sunday morning). St. Philip Neri popularized the practice in Rome, and Pope Clement VIII organized it in 1592 so that it rotated perpetually among Rome's churches, ensuring that the Blessed Sacrament was always exposed somewhere in the city. The devotion spread throughout the Catholic world and became a regular feature of parish life, typically celebrated annually with solemn exposition, continuous prayer, scheduled Holy Hours, preaching, Confession availability, and a concluding procession and Benediction. In the United States, the Forty Hours became one of the most important parish events of the year, especially in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.",
    example: "In a nineteenth-century Philadelphia parish, the Forty Hours Devotion transformed the church: altars were decorated with hundreds of candles, parishioners signed up for hourly shifts of adoration day and night, a visiting preacher gave missions, and the concluding Eucharistic procession drew the entire neighborhood.",
    whyItMatters: "The Forty Hours Devotion represents the Church's most sustained communal act of Eucharistic adoration, deepening faith in the Real Presence and drawing entire parishes into extended contemplation of Christ's sacrificial love.",
    relatedTerms: ["mex-perpetual-adoration-movement", "mex-novena-practice-origins", "mex-triduum-devotional"]
