    body: "Gallicanism was a complex of ideas and practices asserting the liberties of the French (Gallican) Church vis-a-vis the papacy. Its roots lie in the medieval conflict between Philip IV of France and Pope Boniface VIII. Gallicanism reached its clearest expression in the Four Gallican Articles of 1682, drafted by Bishop Jacques-Benigne Bossuet at the behest of Louis XIV: (1) popes have no authority over temporal rulers; (2) ecumenical councils are superior to the pope (conciliarism); (3) papal authority is limited by the canons and customs of national churches; and (4) papal judgments in matters of faith are not infallible unless confirmed by the consent of the Church. These articles were required to be taught in all French seminaries and universities. Pope Alexander VIII condemned them in 1690, but they remained influential in France until the Revolution. The definition of papal infallibility at Vatican I (1870) and the ultramontane movement effectively ended Gallicanism as a theological position, though its echoes can be detected in modern debates about episcopal collegiality and decentralization.",
