    body: "Josephinism (named for Emperor Joseph II of the Habsburg Empire) represents the most thorough attempt by an Enlightenment-era Catholic ruler to subordinate the Church to the state while remaining nominally Catholic. Joseph II suppressed over 700 monasteries and convents that he deemed 'unproductive' (those devoted to contemplative life rather than education or hospital work), seized their property, and redirected the revenues to parishes and state-controlled seminaries. He reorganized diocesan boundaries to match civil ones, mandated the number of candles on altars, regulated the length of sermons, prohibited certain devotional practices he considered superstitious, and required all seminarians to attend state-run 'general seminaries' rather than diocesan ones. Pope Pius VI took the extraordinary step of traveling to Vienna in 1782 to confront Joseph personally—to no avail. After Joseph's death in 1790, many of his reforms were reversed, but Josephinist attitudes of state paternalism toward the Church persisted in the Habsburg lands well into the nineteenth century.",
