    body: "Ultramontanism (from the Latin ultra montes, 'beyond the mountains,' i.e., looking beyond the Alps to Rome) was the movement that championed the supreme authority of the Pope over national churches, secular governments, and ecumenical councils. Reacting against Gallicanism, Febronianism, Josephinism, and the French Revolution's assault on the Church, ultramontanists argued that only a strong papacy could protect the Church's freedom and doctrinal integrity. Key figures included Joseph de Maistre (Du Pape, 1819), the Jesuit journal La Civilta Cattolica, Louis Veuillot's L'Univers newspaper, and Cardinal Henry Edward Manning. The movement reached its culmination at the First Vatican Council (1869-1870), which defined both the Pope's universal jurisdiction over the entire Church and his infallibility when speaking ex cathedra on matters of faith and morals. While a minority of bishops (including many Germans and French) opposed the definition as inopportune, the vast majority voted in favor. The Second Vatican Council (1962-1965) complemented Vatican I's teaching on papal primacy with a fuller theology of episcopal collegiality.",
